{
    "question_text": "<h3>Greatest Common Divisor of Strings</h3><p>For two strings <code>s</code> and <code>t</code>, we say \"<code>t</code> divides <code>s</code>\" if and only if <code>s = t + t + t + ... + t</code> (i.e., <code>t</code> is concatenated with itself one or more times).</p><p>Given two strings <code>str1</code> and <code>str2</code>, return the largest string <code>x</code> such that <code>x</code> divides both <code>str1</code> and <code>str2</code>.</p>",
    "difficulty": "EASY",
    "marks": 5,
    "input_format": "First line: string str1. Second line: string str2.",
    "output_format": "A single string representing the GCD string, or empty string if none exists.",
    "constraints": [
        "1 <= str1.length, str2.length <= 1000",
        "str1 and str2 consist of English uppercase letters."
    ],
    "explanation": "The key insight is that if a GCD string exists, then `str1 + str2` must equal `str2 + str1`. If this condition fails, there is no valid GCD string. If it holds, the GCD string length is `gcd(len(str1), len(str2))`, and the answer is `str1[:gcd_len]`. This works because string divisibility mirrors integer divisibility for the lengths. The mathematical GCD computation ensures we find the largest possible divisor. O(N+M) time for the concatenation check, O(log(min(N,M))) for the GCD.",
    "answer": "def solve(str1, str2):\n    from math import gcd\n    if str1 + str2 != str2 + str1:\n        return ''\n    return str1[:gcd(len(str1), len(str2))]",
